I hear you pain around the L3/L4 lumbar area (near the navel) can come from a lot of sources, including:

  • Muscle strain (core, psoas, or lower back muscles)
  • Lumbar disc issues (herniation, bulging disc pressing on nerves)
  • Facet joint irritation
  • Referred pain from abdominal organs (kidneys, intestines, etc.)

If the pain is:

  • Sharp, radiating down your leg, with numbness/weakness could be nerve compression (sciatica).
  • Deep ache that worsens when sitting/standing long could be disc or posture-related.
  • Sudden, severe, or with fever, nausea, or abdominal symptoms that can sometimes mean something more urgent (kidney stone, appendix, aneurysm, etc.).

If its intense, sudden, or new Id strongly recommend getting checked by a doctor or urgent care to rule out the serious stuff.

That actually lines up pretty well with lumbar spine / disc + posture-related pain especially since you mentioned:

  • Deep ache + shooting pain when turning often means nerves are getting irritated (likely from a disc or joint at L3L4/L4L5).
  • Worse on a soft bed your lower back sags down when you sleep on your stomach, which hyperextends the lumbar spine (bends it backward too much). Over time, that can really aggravate the discs and facet joints.
  • Feels bent the wrong way yep, thats classic hyperextension stress.

Things you can try (short-term relief):

  • Sleep adjustment:

    • If you must sleep on your stomach, put a thin pillow under your hips/pelvis this helps keep the spine neutral instead of arched.
    • If possible, try your side with a pillow between your knees much kinder on the lumbar spine.

  • During the day:

    • Avoid long sitting in a slouched position; keep lumbar support (rolled-up towel behind lower back).
    • Heat pad (for muscle relaxation) or alternating ice (for inflammation) depending on what feels better.

  • Gentle movements:

    • Knee-to-chest stretch (lying on your back, pull knees gently toward chest).
    • Pelvic tilts (lying on your back, press lower back gently into the floor).
    • Childs pose (if comfortable) to lengthen the spine.

Red flags (get checked quickly if):

  • Pain shoots down leg with numbness/tingling/weakness.
  • Loss of bladder/bowel control (emergency).
  • Severe, worsening pain that doesnt ease with rest.

Sounds like youre toughing through this, but if it keeps going more than a week or two, or if the shooting pain gets worse, youll want to get imaging (like an MRI) to see if a disc is pressing on a nerve.
